and of the Sangha Trinational in Cameroon.

90
00:07:49,810 --> 00:07:52,089
Note that the protected areas shown on this
map

91
00:07:52,089 --> 00:07:56,599
are surrounded by mining areas, the colored
areas here,

92
00:07:56,599 --> 00:08:02,949
some of which encroach on the very reserves,
despite these being world heritage sites.

93
00:08:02,949 --> 00:08:07,710
One arrives at a situation like this
simply via a lack of coordinated territorial

94
00:08:07,710 --> 00:08:09,199
planning.

95
00:08:09,199 --> 00:08:12,999
which leaves the field open to, in this case,
the Ministry of Mines,

96
00:08:12,999 --> 00:08:16,199
to issue permits which do not take into account
other agreements,

97
00:08:16,199 --> 00:08:19,789
--here, for conservation-- of this territory.

98
00:08:19,789 --> 00:08:23,900
Unfortunately, this is a very common scenario.

99
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:41,919
Let's look at another example in Cameroon,
this time in the north

100
00:08:41,919 --> 00:08:42,930
of the country.

101
00:08:42,930 --> 00:08:56,589
All

102
00:08:56,589 --> 00:09:30,670
of

103
00:09:30,670 --> 00:09:40,029
the 
above also applies to other forms of development:

104
00:09:40,029 --> 00:09:48,380
urbanization, the development of infrastructure,
the spread of agriculture, etc.

105
00:09:48,380 --> 00:09:53,460
Overall territorial planning
must be seen as an absolute necessity for

106
00:09:53,460 --> 00:09:58,020
protected areas
as an "empty-chair" policy has proven to be

107
00:09:58,020 --> 00:10:01,649
clearly catastrophic.

108
00:10:01,649 --> 00:10:07,610
Those who manage protected areas
must learn to leave their territories,

109
00:10:07,610 --> 00:10:13,130
and engage in discussion with all the parties
around them

110
00:10:13,130 --> 00:10:16,360
in order to prevent decisions being made against
them.

